{{globalize/USA|date=March 2013}}
[[Concussion]]s, a type of [[traumatic brain injury]], have been a notorious issue in sports, being a notable reason for player [[suicide]]s and retirements due to [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE) from their playing careers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kingston |first=Gary |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Concussion+sends+Mike+Robertson+into+retirement/6698272/story.html |title=Concussion sends Mike Robertson into retirement |publisher=Vancouversun.com |date=2012-05-29 |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref> A form of CTE common in [[boxing]] is [[dementia pugilistica]] (DP). Over 1.6 million Americans have sustained concussion-related injuries, a number that has since then{{date missing}} grown in high school and college athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/healthy_kids/152611285.html |title=Girls, sports and concussions |publisher=Philly.com |date=2012-05-23 |accessdate=2012-07-14}}</ref> Because of the fact that concussions cannot be seen on X-rays nor CT scans, attempts to prevent concussions have been difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thinkfirst.ca/programs/concussion.aspx |title=Think First - Pensez d'Abord |publisher=Thinkfirst.ca |date= |accessdate=2012-08-04}}</ref> As of 2012, the [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|four major professional sports leagues]] in the United States and Canada have concussion policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/topics/_/page/concussions |title=Concussions in sports - NFL Topics - ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref>

==Policies==
===Major League Baseball===
[[Major League Baseball]]'s policy was first started in 2007, and injured players are examined by a team athletic trainer on the field.<ref name=USAToday>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/2011-04-12-nba-concussions_N.htm |title=Concussions now a hot issue as leagues toughen policies |publisher=Usatoday.Com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref> On March 29, 2011, MLB and the [[Major League Baseball Players Association]] announced that they have created various protocols for the league's concussion policy. The new policy includes four primary components:<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephania BellFantasy SportsFollowArchive |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/fantasy/baseball/flb/story?id=6280590 |title=7-day DL, return-to-play protocols part of MLB's new concussion policy - Fantasy Baseball - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2011-04-01 |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref>
* All teams are to run baseline neurocognitive testing for all players and umpires using the ImPACT (Immediate Post-Concussion Assessment and Cognitive Testing) system during spring training or after a player signing.<ref name=USATodayMLB>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2011/03/baseball-new-concussion-policy-seven-day-disabled-list/1 |title=Baseball establishes seven-day DL in concussion policy |publisher=Content.usatoday.com |date=2011-03-30 |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref>
* The SCAT2 (Sport Concussion Assessment Tool, version 2) has been adopted as the official sideline concussion assessment tool of the league, even though various teams have already adopted this tool.
* The establishment of the 7-day disabled list for players with concussions. Players who have been on the list for 14 days are to be transferred to the 15-day list.<ref name=USATodayMLB />
* Any player who has been diagnosed with a concussion, regardless of being placed on the disabled list, must have his team submit a return-to-play form to the league's medical director to in order for that player to be cleared to play.

===National Basketball Association===
The [[National Basketball Association]] does not have a policy, and team procedures after concussions vary by team.<ref name=USAToday />

===National Football League===
{{main|Concussions in American football}}
The [[National Football League]]'s policy was first started in 2007, and injured players are examined on field by the medical team.<ref name=USAToday /> The league's policy included the "NFL Sidelines Concussion Exam", which requires players who have taken [[Helmet-to-helmet collision|hits to the head]] to perform tests concerning concentration, thinking and balance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thechart.blogs.cnn.com/2011/02/25/new-nfl-concussion-policy-waiting-on-approval/ |title=NFL to require sideline test after head blows – - CNN.com Blogs |publisher=Thechart.blogs.cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref> In 2011, the league introduced an assessment test, which combines a symptoms checklist, a limited neurological examination, a cognitive evaluation, and a balance assessment. For a player to be allowed to return, he must be [[asymptomatic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayer|first=Larry|url=http://www.chicagobears.com/news/article-1/Cutler-on-mend-after-suffering-concussion/d1f132de-7d46-45fc-b7eb-e06e36482121|title=Cutler on mend after suffering concussion|publisher=[[Chicago Bears]]|date=2012-11-12|accessdate=2012-11-12}}</ref>

===National Hockey League===
The [[National Hockey League]]'s concussion policy began in 1997, and players who sustain concussions are evaluated by a team doctor in a quiet room.<ref name=USAToday /> In March of 2011, the NHL adopted guidelines for the league's concussion policy. Before the adoptions, examinations on the bench for concussions was the minimum requirement, but the new guidelines make it mandatory for players showing concussion-like symptoms to be examined by a doctor in the locker room.<ref name=ESPNNHL>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=6411004 |title=NHL commissioner Gary Bettman pleased with league's concussion protocol - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2011-04-23 |accessdate=2012-06-30}}</ref>

{{quote|"We celebrate the big hit, we don't like the big head hit. There is an important distinction because we celebrate [[checking (ice hockey)|body-checking]]."<ref name=ESPNNHL />|NHL Comissioner [[Gary Bettman]]}}

